@benjyw discussed what this option should look like in a V2 world. Originally, we had `--repl-py-ipython` as a bool option that would enable IPython. 

We at first discussed a goal-level option `--repl-ipython`, but that doesn't make sense in the context of JVM, for example. Nor could we come up with a generic option like we have with `--test-coverage`.

Instead, we settled on `--ipython-enabled`. Why not `--ipython-skip`, which we use with linters/formatters? Unlike `lint`, we don't expect to run _multiple REPL tools_ over the same Python target. This comes down to whether you want the standard REPL or the souped-up IPython REPL. Skipping is orthogonal.

This file isn't supposed to be edited directly: see the header.

But also, I think this is a blocker for landing: we don't control the stack size of users in the wild, and so users would need to set this environment variable in `pants` scripts, etc in order to avoid explosions. I'd also be worried about efficiency.

https://without.boats/blog/futures-and-segmented-stacks/#segmenting-your-futures-for-fun-and-profit explains the problem, and mentions that the solution is to use `BoxFuture`. It's not clear where in the stack we should do this, but it amounts to:
```rust
// from
async fn ... () -> Result<..> {
 ..
}

// to
fn ..() -> BoxFuture<Result<..>> {
  async move { .. }.boxed()
}
```

Experimenting with applying that transform in a few places and seeing how much it affects the stack size might be good?

